  aThis timely and accessible book explores the links between politics, learning and sustainability. Its central focus is the future of people and the planet itself. The challenges that we face in combatting climate change and building a more sustainable world are complex and the book argues that if we are to successfully meet these challenges we need a fundamental change in the way we do politics and economics, embedding a lifelong commitment to sustainability in all learning. We have no option but to make things work for the better. After all, planet earth is the only home we have! The book will be important reading for academics and students in a variety of related subjects, including politics, public policy, education, sustainable development, geography, media, international relations and development studies. It will also be a valuable resource for NGOs and policy makers.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aEnvironmental education. 0aEnvironmental responsibility. 0aSustainabilityxPolitical aspects. 0aSustainability. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Environmental Policy.2bisacsh1 aAtkinson, Hugh, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAtkinson, Hugh, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBenko, Lyle M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlewitt, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIchinose, Tomonori, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKoganezawa, Takaaki, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMuhumaza, Vincent, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMusange, Chikondi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOtieno, Mary, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/v